## Conclusion

Pollution, primarily from land-based nutrient inputs via the Yangtze River and coastal industrial and agricultural activities, has profoundly impacted the East China Sea ecosystem. The increased nutrient loads have driven severe coastal eutrophication, leading to frequent harmful algal blooms, oxygen depletion, and shifts in biological communities. These changes threaten biodiversity, fisheries, and the overall health of the marine environment. While recent control measures have begun to mitigate these impacts, the legacy of nutrient accumulation and ecosystem response lags mean that recovery will be gradual. Continued monitoring, integrated pollution management, and ecosystem-based approaches are essential to protect and restore the East China Sea’s environmental quality.

